voiphandset (0.2.4-1) oracular; urgency=medium

  * Fix: cradle-down didn't restore audio to the base speaker if the
    call-state machine had ever entered HANDSET state (e.g. via an
    accidental green-dial press, or via a real call). The polled
    cradle event was only updating the lifted flag, not driving the
    HANDSET → IDLE / HOLDING → SPEAKERPHONE state transitions. Added
    Router.on_cradle_change() which does both.

  * Fix: writes to the route bit (HID feature-report bit 0) are now
    forced through to the device on every Router._apply(), even when
    the cached feature byte already matches the desired value. The
    old skip-no-op optimization was masking a divergence between our
    cached state and the device's actual state, leaving the route
    stuck on earpiece after re-cradle.

 -- Jason Jorgenson <jjorgenson@gmail.com>  Tue, 12 May 2026 14:55:00 +0000

voiphandset (0.2.3-1) oracular; urgency=medium

  * Add cradle-state polling: a CradleMonitor thread reads byte[2]
    of the 64-byte feature report every 500 ms. Fixes the issue where
    putting the handset back in the cradle without first pressing
    red-hangup didn't return audio routing to the base speaker — the
    HID interrupt endpoint doesn't fire an event in that case, so the
    cradle state has to be polled.
  * Add handlers for the VOL+ / VOL- buttons on the base unit.
    Pressing them now changes the device's PulseAudio sink volume
    by ±5 %. Auto-repeat works as expected when the button is held.
  * Add handler for the MUTE button on the handset. Toggles mic mute
    via PulseAudio and syncs the mute LED (bit 6 of the HID feature
    report) to match. Initial mute state is read from PulseAudio on
    daemon startup.
  * New modules: voiphandset.cradle_monitor, voiphandset.controls.
  * Depends: pulseaudio-utils (already in 0.2.2).

 -- Jason Jorgenson <jjorgenson@gmail.com>  Tue, 12 May 2026 14:15:00 +0000

voiphandset (0.2.2-1) oracular; urgency=medium

  * Fix: ring engine now plays through PipeWire (paplay) instead of
    direct kernel ALSA. The PipeWire loopback module that backs the
    speakerphone virtual sink holds the kernel device exclusively, so
    aplay's plughw access was failing silently.

 -- Jason Jorgenson <jjorgenson@gmail.com>  Tue, 12 May 2026 13:25:00 +0000

voiphandset (0.2.1-1) oracular; urgency=medium

  * Fix: D-Bus name registration broke because BecomeMonitor() was being
    called on the same connection that owned the service name, putting
    it into read-only mode. Now uses two private SessionBus connections.
  * Fix: ring engine notifies the router when it finishes naturally, so
    call_state correctly returns to IDLE.
  * PipeWire loopback target updated to the iec958-stereo profile name.

 -- Jason Jorgenson <jjorgenson@gmail.com>  Tue, 12 May 2026 13:15:00 +0000

voiphandset (0.2.0-1) oracular; urgency=medium

  * Initial Debian packaging.
  * Refactor into voiphandset Python package; install handset script.
  * Add D-Bus IPC interface (com.arkygeek.Handset).
  * Add PipeWire loopback config for "HP Handset (Speakerphone)" sink.
  * Add call-state machine (idle/ringing/handset/holding/speakerphone).
  * Auto bit-0 routing based on cradle state and PipeWire stream activity.
  * Ring on incoming Rambox WhatsApp calls (US ring); Messenger burst
    heuristic (UK ring) for 3-in-10s notifications.

 -- Jason Jorgenson <jjorgenson@gmail.com>  Tue, 12 May 2026 12:00:00 +0000
